title: [PDF] The Rise of Open Science: Tracking the Evolution and Perceived Value of Data and Methods Link-Sharing Practices | Semantic Scholar

# \[PDF\] The Rise of Open Science: Tracking the Evolution and Perceived Value of Data and Methods Link-Sharing Practices | Semantic Scholar

[

### An analysis of the effects of sharing research data, code, and preprints on citations

](/paper/An-analysis-of-the-effects-of-sharing-research-and-Colavizza-Cadwallader/955f29b7d859d70c459d109248c386e2aef5187f)

Computer Science

-   2024

It is found that the early release of a publication as a preprint correlates with a significant positive citation advantage, and sharing data in an online repository correlates with a smaller yet still positive citation advantage, however, it is not found that sharing code in an online repository correlates with a significant citation advantage.

[](/reader/955f29b7d859d70c459d109248c386e2aef5187f)\[PDF\]

[

### Open Data Science

](/paper/Open-Data-Science-Lahti/0a4b3c33e830d8cde364443a52e673c2c07dcfe8)

[Leo Lahti](/author/Leo-Lahti/2288483979)

Computer Science, Environmental Science

-   2018

Drawing insights from a decade of community engagement, the concept of open data science is proposed, which refers to the new forms of research enabled by open data, open methods, and open collaboration.

      <meta name="description" content="A large-scale dataset of 1.1M papers from arXiv that are representative of the fields of physics, math, and computer science is analyzed to analyze the adoption of data and method link-sharing practices over time and their impact on article reception. In recent years, funding agencies and journals increasingly advocate for open science practices (e.g. data and method sharing) to improve the transparency, access, and reproducibility of science. However, quantifying these practices at scale has proven difficult. In this work, we leverage a large-scale dataset of 1.1M papers from arXiv that are representative of the fields of physics, math, and computer science to analyze the adoption of data and method link-sharing practices over time and their impact on article reception. To identify links to data and methods, we train a neural text classification model to automatically classify URL types based on contextual mentions in papers. We find evidence that the practice of link-sharing to methods and data is spreading as more papers include such URLs over time. Reproducibility efforts may also be spreading because the same links are being increasingly reused across papers (especially in computer science); and these links are increasingly concentrated within fewer web domains (e.g. Github) over time. Lastly, articles that share data and method links receive increased recognition in terms of citation count, with a stronger effect when the shared links are active (rather than defunct). Together, these findings demonstrate the increased spread and perceived value of data and method sharing practices in open science.">

In recent years, funding agencies and journals increasingly advocate for open science practices (e.g. data and method sharing) to improve the transparency, access, and reproducibility of science. However, quantifying these practices at scale has proven difficult. In this work, we leverage a large-scale dataset of 1.1M papers from arXiv that are representative of the fields of physics, math, and computer science to analyze the adoption of data and method link-sharing practices over time and their impact on article reception. To identify links to data and methods, we train a neural text classification model to automatically classify URL types based on contextual mentions in papers. We find evidence that the practice of link-sharing to methods and data is spreading as more papers include such URLs over time. Reproducibility efforts may also be spreading because the same links are being increasingly reused across papers (especially in computer science); and these links are increasingly concentrated within fewer web domains (e.g. Github) over time. Lastly, articles that share data and method links receive increased recognition in terms of citation count, with a stronger effect when the shared links are active (rather than defunct). Together, these findings demonstrate the increased spread and perceived value of data and method sharing practices in open science.","author":[{"@type":"Person","name":"Hancheng Cao","mainEntityOfPage":"/author/Hancheng-Cao/2256613265"},{"@type":"Person","name":"Jesse Dodge","mainEntityOfPage":"/author/Jesse-Dodge/34176020"},{"@type":"Person","name":"Kyle Lo","mainEntityOfPage":"/author/Kyle-Lo/46258841"},{"@type":"Person","name":"Daniel A.
